# Title: JavaScript: The definitive guide to array

## Definition:
An array is an ordered collection of values stored in a single variable.

## Purpose: 
Use an array when:
- items are related.
- order matters.
- you need to access items by position.

## Create arrays
There are several methods of creating arrays. I will cover them starting with the most common approaches.

### Array Literals
Array literals are comman-separated lists of elements wrapped in square brackets.

```javascript
const hasNoValues = []; // An array contains no elements. A container exists but has no items.

const worldWarIIEndDate = [2, 9, 1945]; // An array contains only numeric values.

const mustSeeHeritageSitesInVietnam = [
	"The Complex of Hue Monuments",
	"Ha Long Bay",
	"Phong Nha - Ke Bang National Park",
	"Trang An Landscape Complex",
	"Hoi An Ancient Town",
]; // An array contains only string values.

const mixedTypes = [5, "minute boil", "simmer for", 3, "hours", true, "🍜"]; // An array contains elements of multiple types.
```

✨ Array elements whose values are omitted create empty slots that behave differently from `undefined`.
```javascript
// An array has one missing element at index 3. This is called a sparse array.
const fibonacci = [0,1,1,,3,5,8];
// [0, 1, 1, <1 empty slot>, 3, 5, 8]
```

### Spread operator
The spread operator allows you to include elements of an array within an array literal.
```javascript
const northHighlands = ["Ha Giang", "Sapa"];
const centralCoast = ["Da Nang", "Hue", "Hoi An"];
const southernDelta = ["Can Tho", "Ba Ria - Vung Tau"];

// Use spread to combine all regions into one map.
const vietnamGeography = [...northHighlands, ...centralCoast, ...southernDelta];
// [ "Ha Giang", "Sapa", "Da Nang", "Hue", "Hoi An", "Can Tho", "Vung Tau" ]
```

It is also extremely convenient for create a shallow copy of an array.
```javascript
const physicists = [{ fullName: "Galileo Galilei" }, { fullName: "Max Well" }, { fullName: "Albert Einstein" }, { fullName: "Michael Faraday" }];

// Create a shallow copy from a list of greatest physicists.
const physicistsCopy = [...physicists]; 

// Change the top-level element is not reflected in the original.
physicistsCopy[1] = { fullName: "Paul Dirac" };

physicists[1].fullName
// "Max Well"

// Change properties of the nested object does affect the original.
physicistsCopy[0].fullName = "Isaac Newton"

physicists[0].fullName
// "Isaac Newton"
```

If you're curious about shallow copying, I'll write a dedicated post about it.

### Array() constructor
Another way to create an array is by using the `Array()` constructor. I rarely use it in real-world code.

You can create an empty array by invoking `Array()` constructor with no arguments. It is equivalent to the empty array literal `[]`.
```javascript
const hasNoValues = new Array();
```

You can pass two or more arguments, or a single non-numeric argument. Those values will become elements of the new array. 
```javascript
const worldHeritageSitesInChina = new Array("Mount Taishan", "The Great Wall", "Forbidden City", "Summer Palace", "West Lake");
```

### Array.of()
The `Array()` constructor does not create an array with a single numeric value. Instead, it treats that number as the array's length. `Array.of()` addresses this problem.

It always return a new array whose elements are exactly the arguments passed to it, regards of their number of types.
```javascript
const singleNum = Array.of(1975);
// [1975] 
```

It also works with mixed types.
```javascript
const mixedTypes = Array.of("Grand Canyon National Park", 1978, "Arizona", { isSpectacular: true });
```

